''Tis no matter for that , said Robin 'I love the girl , and I will never please my pocket in marrying , and not please my fancy . 
'And so , my dear , adds he , 'there is no opposing him . 
'Why , says I , smiling , 'I can stop all their mouths at one clap by telling him , and them too , that I am married already to his elder brother . 
He smiled a little too at the word , but I could see it startled him , and he could not hide the disorder it put him into . 
'No , no , says I pleasantly , 'I am not so fond of letting the secret come out without your consent . 
When I was fully recovered he began again . 
I could not deny a word of this , and had nothing to say to it in general . 
'Your dear whore , says I , 'you would have said if you had gone on , and you might as well have said it but I understand you . 
You know and cannot but remember that these have been your own words to me . 
I found this was a little too close upon him , but I made it up in what follows . 
'Why , then , my dear , says he , 'we have no time to talk further now . 
Consider of it , and think closely about it I cannot but be of the opinion still , that it will be the best course you can take . 
They had on this occasion a squabble one day about me at table , that had like to have put the whole family in an uproar , and for some time did so . 
They happened to be all at table but the father as for me , I was ill , and in my chamber . 
'Alas , says the old lady , 'that poor girl ! I am afraid she will never be well . 
'Well ! says the elder brother , 'how should Mrs. Betty be well ? They say she is in love . 
'I believe nothing of it , says the old gentlewoman . 
'Why , sister , you must acknowledge she is very handsome , says the elder brother . 
'Ay , and a great deal handsomer than you , sister , says Robin , 'and that's your mortification . 
'I would she was in love with me , says Robin 'I'd quickly put her out of her pain . 
So there was her mouth stopped . 
'I find , says the eldest sister , 'if Betty is not in love , my brother is . 
Robin replied , that was business for the master and mistress of the family , who where not to be taught by one that had so little judgment as his eldest sister . 
It ran up a great deal farther the sister scolded , Robin rallied and bantered , but poor Betty lost ground by it extremely in the family . 
I heard of it , and I cried heartily , and the old lady came up to me , somebody having told her that I was so much concerned about it . 
I told her I would , with all my heart , and with the utmost plainness and sincerity . 
Why , then , the question was , whether there way anything between her son Robert and me . 
I told her I lover her hugely , says he , 'but I could never make the jade believe I was in earnest . 
'Well , says the mother , 'then there's one son lost' and she said it in a very mournful tone , as one greatly concerned at it . 
'I hope not , madam , says Robin 'no man is lost when a good wife has found him . 
'Why , but , child , says the old lady , 'she is a beggar . 
'Why , then , madam , she has the more need of charity , says Robin 'I'll take her off the hands of the parish , and she and I'll beg together . 
'It's bad jesting with such things , says the mother . 
'I don't jest , madam , says Robin . 
'We'll come and beg your pardon , madam and your blessing , madam , and my father's . 
'This is all out of the way , son , says the mother . 
'If you are in earnest you are undone . 
'That's a fine tale , indeed she is not so far out of her senses neither . 
Mrs. Betty is no fool , says the younger sister . 
