He was in a might good humour when he heard me say I had paid her , and it went off into some other discourse at that time . 
But the next morning , he having heard me up about my room before him , he called to me , and I answering , he asked me to come into his chamber . 
After some very kind expressions , he asked me if I would be very honest to him , and give a sincere answer to one thing he would desire of me . 
After some little cavil at the word 'sincere , and asking him if I had ever given him any answers which were not sincere , I promised him I would . 
Why , then , his request was , he said , to let him see my purse . 
I immediately put my hand into my pocket , and , laughing to him , pulled it out , and there was in it three guineas and a half . 
Then he asked me if there was all the money I had . 
I told him No , laughing again , not by a great deal . 
Well , then , he said , he would have me promise to go and fetch him all the money I had , every farthing . 
In which drawer there was a great deal of money in gold , I believe near two hundred guineas , but I knew not how much . 
He took the drawer , and taking my hand , made me put it in and take a whole handful . 
I relate this story the more particularly because of the good humour there was in it , and to show the temper with which we conversed . 
I told him I must housewife the money he had lent me , or else I should not be able to pay him again . 
I was not very easy in that proposal , not knowing what posture I was to live in there , or how he might use me . 
He consented , and I brought him to the Bath , which was about fifteen miles , as I remember . 
However , at last he grew better , and gave hopes that he would recover , as indeed he did , though very slowly . 
And now he made deep protestations of a sincere inviolable affection for me , but all along attested it to be with the utmost reserve for my virtue and his own . 
I told him I was fully satisfied of it . 
At last , repeating his usual saying , that he could lie naked in the bed with me and not offer me the least injury , he starts out of his bed . 
I own it was a noble principle , but as it was what I never understood before , so it was to me perfectly amazing . 
I do not say that I was so wholly pleased with it as he thought I was , for I own much wickeder than he , as you shall hear presently . 
that I could find in my heart to discharge him of his engagement for one night and no more . 
Thus the government of our virtue was broken , and I exchanged the place of friend for that unmusical , harsh sounding title of whore . 
